provenance.p:
A 200 once made up one of the halves of a single manuscript - the second half of which now constitutes no. 400 of Växjö stiftsbibliotek (formerly Kungliga gymnasi biblioteket) - which hails from the Carthusian charterhouse of Salvatorberg in Erfurt; it is listed in their library catalogue as 112.2 (
                                    Lehmann (1935)

                                ). A former librarian notes that the Växjö manuscript (no. 400) retains the original binding, which carries the Carthusian signum as well as a note on the purchase of the manuscript by George Stephens from a Hr Schmidt, Bookseller in Halle in .

The original manuscript appears to have been intact when it was sold at auction in  as part of the library of book collector Friedrich Gottlieb Julius von Bülow (
                                    Schäffer (1836)


                                 ). Presumably, it had come into von Bülow's possession earlier in the 19th century, when the charterhouse of Salvatorberg was secularized.

note.p:
                    The authorship of the text is debated; it has been attributed to, among others, Denis the Carthusian (1402-1471). Emery, however, argues based on the date of the watermark that the text cannot be by Denis (
    Emery 1991

).
